title: Homotopy coherent companionships and conjunctions

sections.text:
#### Abstract

We demonstrate that companionships and conjunctions in double $\infty$-categories - and more generally, in double Segal spaces - extend to functors out of the free-living companionship and conjunction respectively. Specifically, we prove that these extensions are (homotopically) unique: the corresponding spaces of extensions are contractible under suitable completeness assumptions. The developed theory is then put to use to give a characterization of companions and conjoints in functor double Segal spaces in terms of so-called companionable and conjointable 2-cells. We end with an application of our results to $(\infty, 2)$-category theory.

## 1. Introduction

Double $\infty$-categories are two-dimensional $\infty$-categorical structures with objects, two directions of 1-cells: a horizontal and vertical direction, and a notion of 2-cells. They are the weak $\infty$-categorical generalizations of Ehresmann's strict double categories [Ehr63], and were first introduced in the Ph.D. thesis of Haugseng [Hau13]. It is shown by Moser [Mos20] that the strict double categories embed fully faithfully into double $\infty$ categories. In a precise sense, double $\infty$-categories can be viewed as a generalization of $(\infty, 2)$-categories, which admit now two distinct directions for arrows. There are many examples of double $\infty$-categories. For instance, in [Hau18], Haugseng constructs the double $\infty$-categories of spans. In the realm of higher algebra, there are double $\infty$-categories of algebras, maps of algebras and bimodules [Lur17, Section 4.4]. In [Rui23], we discuss the construction of the double $\infty$-category of $\infty$-categories, functors and profunctors, as well as an internal variant. More generally, Haugseng constructs a double $\infty$-category of suitably enriched $\infty$-categories in [Hau16].
1.1. Double Segal spaces and the cartesian closed structure. Throughout this article, we will view double $\infty$-categories as special kinds of double Segal spaces. From this point of view, double $\infty$-categories are double Segal spaces with an extra completeness or univalence condition. A self-contained and detailed introduction to double Segal spaces, alongside with the different variations on completeness, is found in Section 3.

In particular, we will demonstrate here that the ambient $\infty$-category

of double Segal spaces is cartesian closed. To do so, we will use the language of exponential ideals, to be recollected in Section 2, and verify that various localizations of double Segal spaces are exponential ideals in the $\infty$-category $\operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)$ of presheaves on $\Delta^{\times 2}$. If $\mathcal{P}$ and $\mathcal{Q}$ are double Segal spaces, then the associated internal hom in $\mathrm{Cat}^{2}(\mathcal{S})$ of functors between $\mathcal{P}$ and $\mathcal{Q}$ is denoted by

$$
\operatorname{Fin}(\mathcal{P}, \mathcal{Q})
$$

This double Segal space of functors may be computed as the internal hom in $\operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)$. The vertical and horizontal arrows of $\mathbb{F}$ un $(\mathcal{P}, \mathcal{Q})$ are called vertical natural transformations and horizontal natural transformations. A horizontal natural transformation $\alpha: h \rightarrow k$ between two functors $h, k: \mathcal{P} \rightarrow \mathcal{Q}$ is compromised of the following data:

- for every object $x \in \mathcal{P}$, a horizontal arrow in $\mathcal{Q}$

$$
\alpha_{x}: h(x) \rightarrow k(x)
$$

- for every vertical arrow $f: x \rightarrow y$ in $\mathcal{P}$, a naturality 2-cell in $\mathcal{Q}$
![img-0.jpeg](img-0.jpeg)
and the data of (usually, infinitely) many coherences. This is a double $\infty$-categorical variant on the notions of vertical and horizontal natural transformations that were studied by Grandis and Paré [GP99] for strict double categories.
1.2. Companionships and conjunctions. The main result of this paper concerns companionships and conjunctions in double Segal spaces. These are double categorical analogs of the adjunctions for 2-categories, and were introduced by Grandis-Paré [GP04] in the strict context. Likewise, these analogs play an important role in the theory and applications of double categories [Shu08] [DPP10] [Vas19]. The notions of companions and conjoints may be readily generalized to the weak $\infty$-categorical setting.

In this higher setting, companions and conjoints were first considered (albeit under a different name) by Gaitsgory and Rozenblyum to set up the ( $\infty, 2$ )-categorical theory for their six-functor formalisms in derived algebraic geometry [GR17]. Moreover, companions and conjoints play a central role in a double $\infty$-categorical approach to formal category theory [Rui23]. In this approach, companionships and conjunctions witness (co)representability of abstract profunctors, i.e. abstract families of presheaves.

A companionship between a vertical arrow $f: x \rightarrow y$ and a horizontal arrow $F: x \rightarrow y$ in a double Segal space $\mathcal{P}$ is witnessed by the following data:
(1) a companionship unit 2-cell
![img-1.jpeg](img-1.jpeg)
(2) a companionship counit 2-cell

(3) an equivalence in the space of 2-cells of $\mathcal{P}$ between the vertical identity 2-cell
![img-2.jpeg](img-2.jpeg)
and the vertical pasting of $\eta$ and $\epsilon$,
(4) an equivalence in the space of 2-cells of $\mathcal{P}$ between the horizontal identity 2-cell
![img-3.jpeg](img-3.jpeg)
and the horizontal pasting of $\eta$ and $\epsilon$.
In this context, $F$ is called the companion of $f$. The equivalences of (3) and (4) witness the triangle identities for the companionship. The terminology is chosen to reflect the similarity with adjunctions. The definition of conjunctions is (formally) dual to the definition of companionships, and will be given in Section 4. We will also consider some examples of companionships and conjunctions in this section.

It is a celebrated result of Riehl and Verity [RV16] that particular choices of adjunction data in an ( $\infty, 2$ )-category uniquely (in the homotopic sense) upgrade to a homotopy coherent adjunction, i.e. a functor out of the free-living adjunction of Schanuel-Street [SS86]. One of the central objectives of this paper is to prove an analogous result for companionships and conjunctions.

We will show that, likewise, every companionship in $\mathcal{P}$ can uniquely be upgraded to a homotopy coherent companionship. Analogously, a homotopy coherent companionship is another name for a functor from the free-living companionship double Segal space

$$
\operatorname{comp}
$$

to $\mathcal{P}$. The double Segal space comp is level-wise discrete and described as follows. The space $\operatorname{comp}_{n, m}$ of $n \times m$ grids of 2 -cells in comp is given by the set

$$
\operatorname{Poset}([n] \times[m],[1])
$$

of maps of posets $[n] \times[m] \rightarrow[1]$. We will show the following results:
Theorem A. Any companionship in a double Segal space $\mathcal{P}$ extends to a homotopy coherent companionship comp $\rightarrow \mathcal{P}$. Moreover, suppose that $\eta$ is a companionship unit. Then the space of functors comp $\rightarrow \mathcal{P}$ extending $\eta$ is contractible.

Theorem B. Suppose that $f$ is a vertical arrow in a locally complete double Segal space $\mathcal{P}$. If $f$ has a companion, then the space of functors comp $\rightarrow \mathcal{P}$ extending $f$ is contractible.

The precise statements appear as Theorem 4.12 and Theorem 4.13. Note that the above results justify that the double Segal space comp carries the name of the free-living companionship. We will explain in Section 4 that one can use the above results to formally obtain dual results for conjunctions. In this case, the double Segal space comp is replaced by its appropriate dual, the free-living conjunction, denoted by

$$
\text { conj. }
$$

We will elucidate the relation of our results to the work of Riehl-Verity [RV16] in Remark 4.19.

1.3. Companions of vertical natural transformations. We will use the results of Section 4 in Section 5 to study companions (and dually, conjoints) in functor double Segal spaces. The key step is the introduction of the notion of companionable and conjointable 2-cells in a double Segal space. In a precise sense, this is a double $\infty$-categorical variant on the ( $\infty, 2$ )-categorical notion of adjointability [Lur09a, Definition 7.3.1.2] for lax commutative squares. We will explain this in Example 5.2. The main result of Section 5 is the following:

Theorem C. Let $\mathcal{P}$ and $\mathcal{Q}$ be double Segal spaces, so that $\mathcal{Q}$ is locally complete. Suppose that $\alpha: h \rightarrow k$ is a horizontal natural transformation between functors $h, k: \mathcal{P} \rightarrow \mathcal{Q}$. Then the following assertions are equivalent:
(1) $\alpha$ is a companion in $\mathbb{F} \operatorname{un}(\mathcal{P}, \mathcal{Q})$,
(2) for every vertical arrow $f: x \rightarrow y$ in $\mathcal{P}$, the associated naturality 2-cell
![img-4.jpeg](img-4.jpeg)
is companionable in $\mathcal{Q}$.
The precise statement appears as Theorem 5.4 in the paper.
1.4. An application to ( $\infty, 2$ )-category theory. As evident in the work of GaitsgoryRozenblyum [GR17], having good foundations of double $\infty$-categories can be fruitful in building the theory of ( $\infty, 2$ )-categories. We will attest to this principle by giving the following application of Theorem C to ( $\infty, 2$ )-category theory.

Firstly, we will show in Section 6 that, given ( $\infty, 2$ )-categories $\mathcal{X}$ and $\mathcal{Y}$, one can construct an associated double $\infty$-category

$$
\mathbb{F} \text { un }^{\operatorname{lax}}(\mathcal{X}, \mathcal{Y})
$$

as a certain functor double $\infty$-category, such that:

- its objects are functors $\mathcal{X} \rightarrow \mathcal{Y}$,
- its vertical arrows are natural transformations,
- its horizontal arrows are lax natural transformations.

Here, the lax natural transformations are defined using a double categorical construction of the Gray tensor product that is due to Gaitsgory-Rozenblyum. The horizontal fragment is given by the ( $\infty, 2$ )-category $\operatorname{FUN}^{\operatorname{lax}}(\mathcal{X}, \mathcal{Y})$ of functors and lax natural transformations. We will show that Theorem C can be applied to give a quick, double categorical proof of the following theorem of Haugseng [Hau21]:
Theorem D. Let $\beta: k \rightarrow h$ be a lax natural transformation between functors $k, h: \mathcal{X} \rightarrow \mathcal{Y}$. Then the following assertions are equivalent:
(1) $\beta$ is a right adjoint in $\operatorname{FUN}^{\operatorname{lax}}(\mathcal{X}, \mathcal{Y})$,
(2) for any arrow $f: x \rightarrow y$ in $\mathcal{X}$, the horizontal morphisms in the lax square
![img-5.jpeg](img-5.jpeg)
admit left adjoints and the associated mate of the square is an equivalence.

Conventions. We will use the language of $\infty$-categories as developed by Joyal and Lurie. Moreover, we use the following notational conventions:

- The $\infty$-categories of spaces (i.e. $\infty$-groupoids) and $\infty$-categories are denoted by $\mathcal{S}$ and $\mathrm{Cat}_{\infty}$ respectively.
- For an $\infty$-category $\mathcal{C}$, we write $\operatorname{PSh}(\mathcal{C}):=\operatorname{Fun}(\mathcal{C}^{\mathrm{op}}, \mathcal{S})$ for the $\infty$-category of presheaves on $\mathcal{C}$.
- We will use uppercase notation for $(\infty, 2)$-categorical upgrades of particular $\infty$ categories. The double $\infty$-categorical variants will be decorated with blackboard bolds. For instance, in this article, we will see both the $(\infty, 2)$-category $\mathrm{CAT}_{\infty}$ and the double $\infty$-category $\mathbb{C a t}_{\infty}$ of $\infty$-categories.

# 2. Preliminaries on Exponentialality 

This first section is dedicated to reviewing and collecting both the definitions and basic results concerning exponentiable objects and ideals in $\infty$-categories, and (locally) cartesian closed $\infty$-categories.
Definition 2.1. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be an $\infty$-category with finite products. Then an object $x \in \mathcal{C}$ is called exponentiable if the functor $x \times(-): \mathcal{C} \rightarrow \mathcal{C}$ admits a right adjoint. If all objects in $\mathcal{C}$ are exponentiable, then $\mathcal{C}$ is called cartesian closed.

Notation 2.2. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a cartesian closed $\infty$-category. Then we will denote the internal hom functor by

$$
\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}: \mathcal{C}^{\mathrm{op}} \times \mathcal{C} \rightarrow \mathcal{C}
$$

which has the defining property that its composite with the Yoneda embedding $\mathcal{C} \rightarrow$ $\operatorname{PSh}(\mathcal{C})$ is given by

$$
\mathcal{C}^{\mathrm{op}} \times \mathcal{C} \rightarrow \operatorname{PSh}(\mathcal{C}):(x, y) \mapsto \operatorname{Map}_{\mathcal{C}}((-) \times x, y)
$$

There is also a local notion of exponentiability. To this end, note that if $\mathcal{C}$ is an $\infty$ category with pullbacks then all its slices admit finite products and these are computed by pullbacks in $\mathcal{C}$.
Proposition 2.3. Suppose that $f: x \rightarrow y$ is an arrow in an $\infty$-category $\mathcal{C}$ with pullbacks. Then the following assertions are equivalent:
(1) the functor $f^{*}: \mathcal{C} / y \rightarrow \mathcal{C} / x$ admits a right adjoint,
(2) the arrow $f$ is exponentiable when viewed as an object of $\mathcal{C} / y$,
(3) for every arrow $g: a \rightarrow y$, the functor $\left(f^{*} g\right)^{*}: \mathcal{C} / a \rightarrow \mathcal{C} /\left(a \times_{y} x\right)$ admits a right adjoint.

Proof. The product functor $f \times(-): \mathcal{C} / y \rightarrow \mathcal{C} / y$ decomposes as a composite

$$
\mathcal{C} / y \xrightarrow{f^{*}} \mathcal{C} / x \xrightarrow{f_{1}} \mathcal{C} / y
$$

and this proves that (1) implies (2). It is clear that (3) implies (1). Hence, it remains to show that (2) implies (3). Suppose that we have an adjunction

$$
f \times(-): \mathcal{C} / y \rightleftarrows \mathcal{C} / y:[f,-]
$$

with unit $\eta$. Let $g: a \rightarrow y$ be an arrow. Passing to slices over $g$ gives rise to an adjunction

$$
\mathcal{C} / a \simeq(\mathcal{C} / y) / g \rightleftarrows(\mathcal{C} / y) /(f \times g) \simeq \mathcal{C} /\left(a \times_{y} x\right)
$$

where the right adjoint is given by the composite

$$
(\mathcal{C} / y) /(f \times g) \xrightarrow{[f,-]}(C / y) /[f, f \times g] \xrightarrow{\eta_{g}^{\prime}}(\mathcal{C} / y) / g
$$

on account of [Lur09a, Proposition 5.2.5.1]. The left adjoint is precisely given by base change along $f^{*} g$.
Definition 2.4. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be an $\infty$-category with pullbacks. Then an arrow $f: x \rightarrow y$ in $\mathcal{C}$ is called exponentiable if the equivalent conditions of Proposition 2.3 are met. If every arrow in $\mathcal{C}$ is exponentiable, then $\mathcal{C}$ is called locally cartesian closed.
Example 2.5. The exponentiable arrows in $\mathrm{Cat}_{\infty}$ are also called Conduché fibrations. They were studied by Ayala and Francis in [AF20] and by Lurie in [Lur17, Section B.3].
Example 2.6. Since colimits in $\infty$-toposes are universal, all $\infty$-toposes are locally cartesian closed.

We highlight the following implications of Proposition 2.3:
Corollary 2.7. The class of exponentiable arrows in an $\infty$-category with pullbacks is closed under pullbacks.
Corollary 2.8. An $\infty$-category $\mathcal{C}$ with pullbacks is locally cartesian closed if and only if the slice $\mathcal{C} / x$ is cartesian closed for every $x \in \mathcal{C}$.

It will be helpful later in this article, to recognize subcategories of cartesian closed $\infty$-categories that are again cartesian closed. To this end, we will use the formalism of exponential ideals (cf. [Joh02, Section 1.5]).
Definition 2.9. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a cartesian closed $\infty$-category. A fully faithful functor $i: \mathcal{I} \rightarrow \mathcal{C}$ is called an exponential ideal if for every $x \in \mathcal{C}$ and $y \in \mathcal{I}$, the internal hom $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(x, i y)$ is contained in $\mathcal{I}$.

Proposition 2.10. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a cartesian closed $\infty$-category. Suppose that $i: \mathcal{I} \rightarrow \mathcal{C}$ is an exponential ideal so that its essential image is closed under finite products. Then $\mathcal{I}$ is again cartesian closed, and $i$ preserves internal homs.
Proof. Since $i$ is fully faithful, it reflects limits. Hence $\mathcal{I}$ is closed under finite products and $i$ preserves them. It follows that for objects $t, x, y$ in $\mathcal{I}$, we have natural equivalences

$$
\operatorname{Map}_{\mathcal{I}}(t \times x, y) \simeq \operatorname{Map}_{\mathcal{C}}(i t \times i x, i y) \simeq \operatorname{Map}_{\mathcal{C}}\left(i t, \operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(i x, i y)\right)
$$

Since $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(i x, i y)$ is in the image of $i$, the result follows.
Remark 2.11. Note that the full inclusion of a reflective subcategory is always closed under finite products.

The following observation is immediate, and we omit its proof:
Lemma 2.12. Suppose that $i: \mathcal{I} \rightarrow \mathcal{C}$ is a reflective subcategory of a cartesian closed $\infty$ category $\mathcal{C}$, so that $i$ admits a left adjoint $L: \mathcal{C} \rightarrow \mathcal{I}$. Let $x \in \mathcal{C}$ be an object. Then the following assertions are equivalent:
(1) the functor

$$
x \times(-): \mathcal{C} \rightarrow \mathcal{C}
$$

preserves L-local equivalences,
(2) if $S$ is a class of generating L-local equivalences, then $x \times f$ is a L-local equivalence for every $f \in S$,

(3) the functor $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(x,-)$ carries objects in $\mathcal{J}$ to objects in $\mathcal{J}$.

Proposition 2.13. A reflective subcategory $i: \mathcal{J} \rightarrow \mathcal{C}$ is an exponential ideal if and only if the reflector $L: \mathcal{C} \rightarrow \mathcal{J}$ preserves finite products.

Proof. It readily follows from characterization (1) of Lemma 2.12 that $i$ is an exponential ideal if $L$ preserves finite products. Conversely, suppose that $i$ is an exponential ideal. Then we have to show that for any two objects $x, y \in \mathcal{C}$, the canonical comparison map $L(x \times y) \rightarrow L x \times L y$ is an equivalence. Let us denote the unit of the adjunction of $(L, i)$ by $\eta$. Then we obtain a commutative diagram
![img-6.jpeg](img-6.jpeg)

The rightmost vertical arrow is an equivalence since $L$ is a reflector and $i$ preserves finite products. By characterization (1) of Lemma 2.12, the two top horizontal arrows are equivalences as well. Hence, the desired result follows from 2-out-of-3.

# 3. Preliminaries on double Segal spaces 

In this section, we will review and study a selection of types of Barwick's double and 2-fold Segal spaces with different completeness conditions. We will then proceed to show that their ambient $\infty$-categories are cartesian closed by using the theory of exponential ideals that was discussed in Section 2.
3.1. Double Segal spaces. Double Segal spaces arise as certain presheaves on $\Delta^{\times 2}$. Throughout, we will write

$$
[n, m] \in \operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)
$$

for the image of $([n],[m])$ under the Yoneda embedding $\Delta^{\times 2} \rightarrow \operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)$.
Definition 3.1. The presheaves $[0,0],[1,0],[0,1]$ and $[1,1]$ are called the free-living object (or 0-cell), the free-living horizontal and vertical arrow (or 1-cell), and the free-living 2-cell, respectively.

Definition 3.2. A double Segal space is a presheaf on $\operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)$ that is local with respect to the class of following maps:
(Seg) the spine inclusions

$$
[1, m] \cup_{[0, m]}[1, m] \cdots \cup_{[0, m]}[1, m] \rightarrow[n, m]
$$

and

$$
[n, 1] \cup_{[n, 0]}[n, 1] \cdots \cup_{[n, 0]}[n, 1] \rightarrow[n, m]
$$

for $n, m \geq 0$.
We will write

$$
\operatorname{Cat}^{2}(\mathcal{S}) \subset \operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)
$$

for the reflective full subcategory of double Segal spaces.
Remark 3.3. Unraveling the definitions, we observe that a double Segal space $\mathcal{P}$ contains:

- a space $\mathcal{P}_{0,0}$ of objects,
- a space $\mathcal{P}_{0,1}$ of vertical arrows,
- a space $\mathcal{P}_{1,0}$ of horizontal arrows,
- and a space $\mathcal{P}_{1,1}$ of 2-cells.

In general, the Segal condition for $\mathcal{P}$ tells us that we may view $\mathcal{P}_{n, m}$ as a grid of compatible cells. The 2-cells and the compatible arrows of $\mathcal{P}$ that have the same direction may be composed in a mutually compatible and coherently associative fashion. A 2-cell may be pictured as a square
![img-7.jpeg](img-7.jpeg)
where the horizontal/vertical directed arrows are horizontal/vertical arrows of $\mathcal{P}$.
Remark 3.4. Double Segal spaces are generalizations of Rezk's Segal spaces [Rez01]. Recall that the $\infty$-category

$$
\operatorname{Seg}(\mathcal{S}) \subset \operatorname{PSh}(\Delta)
$$

of Segal spaces is defined to be the reflective subcategory generated by the spine inclusions $[1] \cup_{[0]}[1] \cup_{[0]} \cdots \cup_{[0]}[1] \rightarrow[n]$ for $n \geq 0$. Here, we implicitly view every $[n] \in \Delta$ as an object of $\operatorname{PSh}(\Delta)$ via the Yoneda embedding.

Construction 3.5. We will use three involutive operations on $\operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)$ :

$$
(-)^{\mathrm{t}},(-)^{\mathrm{hop}},(-)^{\mathrm{vop}}: \operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right) \rightarrow \operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)
$$

called the transpose, horizontal opposite, and vertical opposite respectively. They are defined by restricting along the functors

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mathrm{t}: \Delta \times \Delta \rightarrow \Delta \times \Delta:([n],[m]) \mapsto([m],[n]) \\
\text { hop }: \Delta \times \Delta \xrightarrow{\text { op } \times \text { id }} \Delta \times \Delta, \quad \text { vop }: \Delta \times \Delta \xrightarrow{\text { id } \times \text { op }} \Delta \times \Delta
\end{gathered}
$$

Here op : $\Delta \rightarrow \Delta$ denotes the usual opposite involution, i.e. it is restricted from the involution functor $(-)^{\text {op }}$ for categories.

One readily verifies that these involutions restrict to involutions

$$
(-)^{\mathrm{t}},(-)^{\mathrm{hop}},(-)^{\mathrm{vop}}: \operatorname{Cat}^{2}(\mathcal{S}) \rightarrow \operatorname{Cat}^{2}(\mathcal{S})
$$

on the $\infty$-category of double Segal spaces.
3.2. Two-fold Segal spaces. As will be dicussed later in further detail, double Segal spaces may be used to obtain Barwick's model of ( $\infty, 2$ )-categories. To this end, we will need to consider the double Segal spaces with only degenerate vertical arrows.

Definition 3.6. A double Segal space $X$ is called a 2-fold Segal space if the structure map

$$
\left(\text { id, } s_{0}\right)^{\star}: X_{0,0} \rightarrow X_{0,1}
$$

is an equivalence. In other words, a presheaf $X \in \operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)$ is a 2 -fold Segal space if it is local with respect to (Seg) of Definition 3.2, and additionally to:
$($ deg $)$ the degeneracy map $[0,1] \rightarrow[0,0]$.
We will write

$$
\operatorname{Seg}^{2}(\mathcal{S}) \subset \operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)
$$

for the reflective subcategory of $\operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)$ spanned by those 2 -fold Segal spaces.
Note that every 2 -fold Segal space $X \in \operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)$ has the feature that the restriction $X_{0, \bullet}$ is an essentially constant simplicial space. It will be convenient to consider the subcategory of such presheaves.

Definition 3.7. We will write

$$
(-)_{h}: \operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)_{\operatorname{deg}} \rightarrow \operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)
$$

for the inclusion of the full subcategory of those presheaves $X \in \operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)$ so that $X_{0, \bullet}$ is essentially constant. This is called the horizontal inclusion functor. Note that this is a inclusion of a reflective subcategory, with generating local maps given by the degeneracy maps $[0, n] \rightarrow[0,0]$ for all $n$.

Construction 3.8. There is also a vertical inclusion functor

$$
(-)_{v}: \operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)_{\operatorname{deg}} \rightarrow \operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)
$$

given by the composite

$$
\operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)_{\operatorname{deg}} \xrightarrow{(-)_{h}} \operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right) \xrightarrow{(-)^{1}} \operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right) \xrightarrow{(-)^{1 \text { dop }}} \operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)
$$

Note that this restricts to a functor $\operatorname{Seg}^{2}(\delta) \rightarrow \operatorname{Cat}^{2}(\delta)$.
Construction 3.9. Let Gaunt ${ }_{2}$ be the full subcategory of the category of 2-categories that is spanned by the gaunt 2-categories. Then one can write down the bicosimplicial object

$$
\Delta^{\times 2} \rightarrow \text { Gaunt }_{2}:([n],[m]) \mapsto[n ; m, \ldots, m]
$$

where $[n ; m \ldots, m]$ denotes the globular 2-category that may be pictured as
![img-8.jpeg](img-8.jpeg)

The restriction to $\{[0]\} \times \Delta$ is constant, so that the we obtain an induced functor

$$
N: \text { Gaunt }_{2} \rightarrow \operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)_{\operatorname{deg}}
$$

so that the image of a gaunt 2 -category $G$ is level-wise described by the set

$$
N G_{n, m}=\operatorname{Hom}([n ; m, \ldots, m], G)
$$

of functors from $[n ; m, \ldots, m]$ to $G$. One readily verifies that the functor $N$ is fully faithful; we will leave the inclusion $N$ implicit throughout this chapter.

Remark 3.10. The obvious commutative square
![img-9.jpeg](img-9.jpeg)
of bisimplicial spaces is a pushout square in $\operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)$, as one readily verifies. If $X$ is a presheaf in $\operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)_{\text {deg }}$, then $X$ is local with respect to the left map in this square. Consequently, $X$ is also local to the right (quotient) map in the square. It follows that the we obtain a natural equivalence

$$
\operatorname{Map}_{\operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)}\left([n ; m \ldots, m]_{h}, X\right) \rightarrow \operatorname{Map}_{\operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)}([n, m], X)=X_{n, m}
$$

This observation implies that $\operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)_{\text {deg }}$ is a presheaf $\infty$-topos. Namely, let $\Theta_{2}^{\prime} \subset$ Gaunt ${ }_{2}$ be the full subcategory spanned by the 2 -categories $[n ; m, \ldots, m], n, m \geq 0$. Then we obtain an adjunction

$$
\operatorname{PSh}\left(\Theta_{2}^{\prime}\right) \rightleftarrows \operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)_{\mathrm{deg}}
$$

where the left adjoint is the cocontinuous extension of the restricted nerve $N \mid \Theta_{2}^{\prime}$, and the right adjoint is induced by restriction along the bicosimplicial object $\Delta^{\times 2} \rightarrow \Theta_{2}^{\prime}$. Using the above, one readily concludes that this sets up an adjoint equivalence.

In turn, this can be used to recover the comparison of [BR20] between 2-fold Segal spaces and $\Theta_{2}$-spaces. Namely, the subcategory $\Theta_{2} \subset$ Gaunt $_{2}$ of loyal disks $\left[n ; m_{1}, \ldots, m_{n}\right]$ (see [Rez10]) is generated by $\Theta_{2}^{\prime}$ under retracts. \Delta^{\mathrm{op}} \rightarrow \mathrm{Cat}_{\infty} \xrightarrow{\operatorname{Fun}(X,-)} \mathrm{Cat}_{\infty}
$$

as a simplicial $\infty$-category (see Remark 3.35). To see this, we note that $X_{v}$ is always a double $\infty$-category and $\left(X_{v}\right)_{n}=X$ for all $n$. Since the functor $[X,-]: \mathrm{DblCat}_{\infty} \rightarrow \mathrm{DblCat}_{\infty}$ is right adjoint to the functor

$$
X_{v} \times(-): \mathrm{DblCat}_{\infty} \rightarrow \mathrm{DblCat}_{\infty}
$$

the observation follows.
Example 3.52. Let $X$ be an $\infty$-category and $\mathcal{C}$ be an $\infty$-category with finite limits. Then we may apply the vertical cotensor construction to the double $\infty$-category $\operatorname{Span}(\mathcal{C})$ of spans that is constructed in [Hau18]. One readily deduces using Remark 3.51 that there is a canonical equivalence of double $\infty$-categories

$$
[X, \operatorname{Span}(\mathcal{C})] \simeq \operatorname{Span}(\operatorname{Fun}(X, \mathcal{C}))
$$

Example 3.53. Let $T$ be an $\infty$-category. We may apply the above construction to the double $\infty$-category $\mathbb{C a t}_{\infty}$ (see Example 3.37) so that we obtain a (locally complete) double $\infty$-category

$$
\left[T^{\mathrm{op}}, \mathbb{C a t}_{\infty}\right]
$$

whose objects are called $T$-indexed $\infty$-categories. Its vertical fragment is given by the $(\infty, 2)$-category of functors $\operatorname{FUN}\left(T^{\mathrm{op}}, \mathrm{CAT}_{\infty}\right)$. It is shown in [Rui23] that $\mathbb{C a t}_{\infty} \simeq \mathbb{C a t}_{\infty}(\mathcal{S})$, so there is an equivalence

$$
\left[T^{\mathrm{op}}, \mathbb{C a t}_{\infty}\right] \simeq\left[T^{\mathrm{op}}, \mathbb{C a t}_{\infty}(\mathcal{S})\right]
$$

See Example 3.37 for the notation. The right hand-side can be identified with the double $\infty$-category $\mathbb{C a t}_{\infty}(\operatorname{PSh}(T))$, as may be concluded directly from the construction of $\mathbb{C a t}_{\infty}(-)$ in [Rui23], so that we obtain an equivalence

$$
\left[T^{\mathrm{op}}, \mathbb{C a t}_{\infty}\right] \simeq \mathbb{C a t}_{\infty}(\operatorname{PSh}(T))
$$

More generally, one can consider the vertical cotensor product

$$
\left[\mathcal{X}^{1-\mathrm{op}}, \mathbb{C a t}_{\infty}\right]
$$

where $\mathcal{X}$ is an $(\infty, 2)$-category. The objects of this double $\infty$-category are functors $\mathcal{X}^{1-\mathrm{op}} \rightarrow$ $\mathrm{CAT}_{\infty}$, and these are usually called 2-presheaves.
3.6. The squares construction. We will make use of the squares functor for 2-fold Segal spaces in this article. In the strict context, this construction goes back to Ehresmann [Ehr63]. It has been studied by Grandis and Paré [GP04], and recently by Guetta-Moser-Sarazola-Verdugo [GMSP23] as well. In the $\infty$-categorical context, it was introduced in the work of Gaitsgory-Rozenblyum on derived algebraic geometry, where it plays an important role in setting up the $(\infty, 2)$-categorical foundations for their treatment of sixfunctor formalisms. It has also been studied recently by Abellán [Abe23].

To define the squares functor, we make use of the gaunt 2-categories
![img-25.jpeg](img-25.jpeg)
which are obtained by taking the oplax Gray tensor product of $[n]$ and $[m]$; see [Gra74] for the original definition. These 2-categories can be organized into a bicosimplicial object

$$
[\cdot] \otimes[\cdot]: \Delta^{\times 2} \rightarrow \operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)_{\operatorname{deg}}:([n],[m]) \mapsto[n] \otimes[m]
$$

We will need the following result:
Proposition 3.54. Let $n, m \geq 1$. Then the canonical maps
(i) $[1] \otimes[m] \cup_{[0] \otimes[m]} \cdots \cup_{[0] \otimes[m]}[1] \otimes[m] \rightarrow[n] \otimes[m]$,
(ii) $[n] \otimes[1] \cup_{[n] \otimes[0]} \cdots \cup_{[n] \otimes[0]}[n] \otimes[1] \rightarrow[n] \otimes[m]$,
are equivalences of 2-fold Segal spaces.
Instead of giving a direct proof of Proposition 3.54 here, we will show how it can be leveraged from the literature. We will make use of the following observation:
Lemma 3.55. Suppose that $f: X \rightarrow Y$ is a map between 2-fold Segal spaces so that:
(1) $f_{0,0}$ is an equivalence of spaces,
(2) $f^{(1)}$ is carried to an equivalence by the reflector $\operatorname{Seg}(\mathcal{S}) \rightarrow \mathrm{Cat}_{\infty}$,
(3) $f$ is carried to an equivalence by the reflector $\operatorname{Seg}^{2}(\mathcal{S}) \rightarrow \mathrm{Cat}_{(\infty, 2)}$.

Then $f$ is an equivalence of 2-fold Segal spaces.
Proof. In light of the Segal condition and assumption (1), we have to verify that $f_{1,0}$ and $f_{1,1}$ are equivalences of spaces. Since (2) holds, the map

$$
X_{1,0} \rightarrow Y_{1,0} \times_{Y_{0,0}^{\times 2}} X_{0,0}^{\times 2}
$$

induced by $f_{1,0}$ must be an equivalence; see [Lur09b, Theorem 1.2.13] for instance. Hence $f_{1,0}$ is an equivalence. In light of [Hau18, Remark 7.19], assumption (1) implies that

$$
X(x, y)_{1} \rightarrow Y(f(x), f(y))_{1} \times_{Y(f(x), f(y))_{0}^{\times 2}} X(x, y)_{0}^{\times 2}
$$

is an equivalence for all objects $x, y \in X$. Recall that the map $X(x, y)_{n} \rightarrow Y(f(x), f(y))_{n}$ is precisely the comparison map

$$
X_{1, n} \rightarrow Y_{1, n} \times_{Y_{0,0}^{\times 2}} X_{0, n}^{\times 2}
$$

on fibers above $(x, y) \in X_{0,0}^{\times 2} \xrightarrow{\simeq} X_{0, n}^{\times 2}$. Since $f_{1,0}$ is an equivalence, it follows that $X(x, y)_{0} \rightarrow$ $Y(x, y)_{0}$ is an equivalence. Thus $X(x, y)_{1} \rightarrow Y(f(x), f(y))_{1}$ must be an equivalence. Since this holds for all $x, y$ in $X$, this in turn implies that $f_{1,1}$ is an equivalence.

Proof. We will just treat map (1); the other one is handled similarly. Let us consider the inclusion

$$
i:[1] \otimes[m] \cup_{[0] \otimes[m]} \cdots \cup_{[0] \otimes[m]}[1] \otimes[m] \rightarrow[n] \otimes[m]
$$

of bisimplicial sets, where the iterated pushout on the left is computed in $\operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)$. Then one readily verifies that $i_{0,0}$ is the identity. Moreover, one can readily show that $i^{(1)}$ lies in the saturated class spanned by the 1-dimensional spine inclusions (see Remark 3.4). Let us consider the reflectors

$$
L: \operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)_{\mathrm{deg}} \rightarrow \operatorname{Seg}^{2}(\mathcal{S}), \quad L^{\prime}: \operatorname{PSh}(\Delta) \rightarrow \operatorname{Seg}(\mathcal{S})
$$

One can verify that the (colimit-preserving) functor $(-)^{(1)}: \operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)_{\text {deg }} \rightarrow \operatorname{PSh}(\Delta)$ carries maps in (Seg) to the saturated class of 1-dimensional spine inclusions. So it follows that $L^{\prime}(L i)^{(1)} \simeq L^{\prime} i^{(1)}$ is an equivalence. A similar argument shows that $(L i)_{0,0}$ is an equivalence, as every map in (Seg) is carried to an equivalence by the evaluation functor $(-)_{0,0}$.

Now, Lemma 3.55 asserts that it is sufficient to check that $L i$ is carried to an equivalence by the reflector $\operatorname{Seg}^{2}(\mathcal{S}) \rightarrow \mathrm{Cat}_{(\infty, 2)}$. This follows from the work of Gagna-HarpazLanari [GHL21] and [HHLN21, Proposition 5.1.9].

Construction 3.56. Since $\operatorname{Seg}^{2}(\mathcal{S})$ is cocomplete, the bicosimplicial object

$$
[\cdot] \otimes[\cdot]: \Delta^{\times 2} \rightarrow \operatorname{Seg}^{2}(\mathcal{S}):([n],[m]) \rightarrow[n] \otimes[m]
$$

extends to a colimit preserving functor $\operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right) \rightarrow \operatorname{Seg}^{2}(\mathcal{S})$. On account of Proposition 3.54, there exists a unique dotted extension in the diagram
![img-26.jpeg](img-26.jpeg)

The horizontal functor admits a right adjoint, which restricts to a right adjoint

$$
\mathrm{Sq}: \operatorname{Seg}^{2}(\mathcal{S}) \rightarrow \operatorname{Cat}^{2}(\mathcal{S})
$$

for Gr. This is called the squares functor. For a 2-fold Segal space $X$, it is level-wise given by

$$
\operatorname{Sq}(X)_{n, m}:=\operatorname{Map}_{\operatorname{Seg}^{2}(\mathcal{S})}([n] \otimes[m], X)
$$

Construction 3.57. There is a canonical functor

$$
\iota_{h}^{n, m}:[n] \otimes[m] \rightarrow[n ; m, \ldots, m]
$$

between gaunt 2-categories that is natural in $([n],[m]) \in \Delta^{\times 2}$. The functor $\iota_{h}^{n, m}$ selects the non-degenerate oplax $n \times m$ grid in $[n ; m, \ldots, m]$ where all the vertical arrows in the grid are identities, pictured as
![img-27.jpeg](img-27.jpeg)

There is also a similarly defined functor

$$
\iota_{v}^{n, m}:[n]^{\mathrm{op}} \otimes[m] \rightarrow[m ; n \ldots, n]
$$

between gaunt 2-categories. The functor $\iota_{v}^{n, m}$ selects the non-degenerate oplax $n \times m$ grid in $[m ; n \ldots, n]$ where all horizontal arrows in the grid are identities, pictured as
![img-28.jpeg](img-28.jpeg)

Let $X$ be a 2-fold Segal space. Then Remark 3.10 implies that $X_{h}$ and $X_{v}$ are (naturally) described by

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \left(X_{h}\right)_{n, m} \simeq \operatorname{Map}_{\mathrm{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)}([n ; m \ldots, m]_{h}, X_{h}) \\
& \left(X_{v}^{\text {hop }}\right)_{n, m} \simeq \operatorname{Map}_{\mathrm{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)}([m ; n \ldots, n]_{v}, X_{v})
\end{aligned}
$$

In light of these descriptions, we can construct maps

$$
X_{h} \rightarrow \operatorname{Sq}(X), \quad X_{v} \rightarrow \operatorname{Sq}(X)
$$

using the natural transformations $\iota_{h}$ and $\iota_{v}$.
Proposition 3.58. Let $X$ be a 2-fold Segal space. The functors $X_{h} \rightarrow \operatorname{Sq}(X)$ and $X_{v} \rightarrow \operatorname{Sq}(X)$ are adjunct to equivalences $X \rightarrow \operatorname-Hor}(\operatorname{Sq}(X))$ and $X \rightarrow \operatorname{Vert}(\operatorname{Sq}(X))$.
Proof. We will just show the statement for the horizontal case; the other case is handled similarly. We have to show that the map

$$
\operatorname{Map}_{\operatorname{Seg}^{2}(\mathcal{S})}([n ; m \ldots, m], X) \rightarrow \operatorname{Map}_{\operatorname{Seg}^{2}(\mathcal{S})}([n ; m, \ldots, m], \operatorname{Hor}(\operatorname{Sq}(X)))
$$

is an equivalence for all $n, m \geq 0$. Note that this map can be identified with the map

$$
\operatorname{Map}_{\mathrm{Cat}^{2}(\mathcal{S})}([n ; m \ldots, m]_{h}, X_{h}) \rightarrow \operatorname{Map}_{\mathrm{Cat}^{2}(\mathcal{S})}([n ; m, \ldots, m]_{h}, \operatorname{Sq}(X))
$$

induced by $X_{h} \rightarrow \operatorname{Sq}(X)$. In light of Remark 3.10, this is an equivalence if and only if the square
![img-29.jpeg](img-29.jpeg)
is a pullback square. By construction of the map $X_{h} \rightarrow \operatorname{Sq}(X)$, this square is obtained from the commutative square
![img-30.jpeg](img-30.jpeg)
of gaunt 2-categories by applying $\operatorname{Map}_{\operatorname{Seg}^{2}(\mathcal{S})}(-, X)$. But this square is a pushout square in $\operatorname{Seg}^{2}(\mathcal{S})$, as argued in [HHLN21, Lemma 5.1.11]. Namely, to show that it is a pushout,

one may reduce to $n, m \in[0,1]$ using the co-Segal condition. The only left-over non-trivial case is $n=m=1$, where it follows from the fact that the canonical map $[1 ; 1] \cup_{[1]^{c}}[2] \rightarrow$ $[1] \otimes[1]$ is an equivalence - already in $\operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)_{\text {deg }}$.
Corollary 3.59. The squares functor restricts to right adjoints $\mathrm{Sq}: \operatorname{Seg}^{2}(\mathcal{S})^{l c} \rightarrow \operatorname{Cat}^{2}(\mathcal{S})^{l c}$ and $\mathrm{Sq}: \mathrm{Cat}_{(\infty, 2)} \rightarrow \mathrm{DblCat}_{\infty}^{\mathrm{c}}$ as well.
Proof. It readily follows from Proposition 3.58 that the squares functor restricts as such. The left adjoints are then given by the composites

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \operatorname{Seg}^{2}(\mathcal{S})^{l c} \rightarrow \operatorname{Seg}^{2}(\mathcal{S}) \xrightarrow{\mathrm{Gr}} \operatorname{Cat}^{2}(\mathcal{S}) \rightarrow \operatorname{Cat}^{2}(\mathcal{S})^{l c} \\
& \operatorname{Cat}_{(\infty, 2)} \rightarrow \operatorname{Seg}^{2}(\mathcal{S}) \xrightarrow{\mathrm{Gr}} \operatorname{Cat}^{2}(\mathcal{S}) \rightarrow \mathrm{DblCat}_{\infty}^{\mathrm{c}}
\end{aligned}
$$

where the functors that appear first and last in the composites are inclusions and localizations respectively.

# 4. Companionships and conjunctions, and homotopy coherence 

Let us start by defining companionships and conjunctions in a double Segal space.
Definition 4.1. Let $f: x \rightarrow y$ be a vertical arrow in a double Segal space $\mathcal{P}$. A horizontal arrow $F: x \rightarrow y$ in $\mathcal{P}$ is called the companion of $f$ if there exist two 2-cells
![img-31.jpeg](img-31.jpeg)
that satisfy the following two triangle identities:
![img-32.jpeg](img-32.jpeg)

In this case, $(f, F)$ is called a companionship, $\eta$ is called the companionship unit, and $\epsilon$ is called the companionship counit.

Dually, a horizontal arrow $F^{\prime}: y \rightarrow x$ is called the conjoint of $f$ when there exist two 2-cells in $\mathcal{P}$
![img-33.jpeg](img-33.jpeg)
that compose as follows:
![img-34.jpeg](img-34.jpeg)

In this case, $\left(f, F^{\prime}\right)$ is called a conjunction, $\eta^{\prime}$ is called the conjunction unit, and $\epsilon^{\prime}$ is called the conjunction counit.

Remark 4.2. These notions were also considered by Gaitsgory and Rozenblyum in [GR17, Subsection 10.5.1], albeit using different terminology.

Remark 4.3. Suppose that $f: x \rightarrow y$ and $F: y \rightarrow x$ are a vertical and horizontal arrow of a double Segal space $\mathcal{P}$ respectively. Then one may easily deduce that the following assertions are equivalent:

- the pair $(f, F)$ forms a conjunction in $\mathcal{P}$,
- the pair $\left(f^{\mathrm{op}}, F\right)$ forms a companionship in $\mathcal{P}^{\mathrm{op}}$,
- the pair $\left(f, F^{\text {op }}\right)$ forms a companionship in $\mathcal{P}^{\text {hop }}$.

Consequently, the theory of companionships is formally dual to the theory of conjunctions.

Remark 4.4. Suppose that $f: x \rightarrow y$ and $g: y \rightarrow z$ are vertical arrows of a double Segal space $\mathcal{P}$, with companions $F$ and $G$ respectively. Then it is instructive to verify $g f$ admits a companion as well, which is given by the composite $G F$. Dually, if $F^{\prime}$ and $G^{\prime}$ are conjoints for $f$ and $g$ respectively, then $g f$ has a conjoint given by $F^{\prime} G^{\prime}$.

Example 4.5. We consider the double Segal space $\operatorname{Sq}(X)$ of squares in a 2-fold Segal space $X$ that was defined in Subsection 3.6. Let $f$ be an arrow of $X$, which we will view as a vertical arrow of $\operatorname{Sq}(X)$. Then one easily checks that the companion of $f$ in $\operatorname{Sq}(X)$ is given by $f$, now viewed as a horizontal arrow. It is also instructive to verify that the conjoint of $f$ in $\operatorname{Sq}(X)$ exists if and only if $f$ admits a right adjoint $g$, in which case the conjoint of $f$ is given by $g$. In that case, the conjunction unit and counit for $(f, g)$ corresponds to the adjunction unit and counit for $(f, g)$.

Example 4.6. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be an $\infty$-category with finite limits. Then we may consider the double $\infty$-category $\operatorname{Span}(\mathcal{C})$ of spans in $\mathcal{C}$ that was constructed in [Hau18]. If $f: x \rightarrow y$ is an arrow of $\mathcal{C}$ that is viewed as a vertical arrow of $\operatorname{Span}(\mathcal{C})$, then it has both a companion and conjoint given by the spans

$$
\left(\mathrm{id}_{x}, f\right): x \rightarrow x \times y, \quad\left(f, \mathrm{id}_{x}\right): x \rightarrow y \times x
$$

Example 4.7. In the double $\infty$-category $\mathbb{C a t}_{\infty}$ of $\infty$-categories that was informally described in Example 3.37, the companion and conjoint of a functor $f: \mathcal{C} \rightarrow \mathcal{D}$ are given by the profunctors

$$
\mathcal{D}^{\mathrm{op}} \times \mathcal{C} \rightarrow \mathcal{S}:(d, c) \mapsto \operatorname{Map}_{\mathcal{D}}(d, f(c)), \quad \mathcal{C}^{\mathrm{op}} \times \mathcal{D} \rightarrow \mathcal{S}:(c, d) \mapsto \operatorname{Map}_{\mathcal{D}}(f(c), d)
$$

respectively. This is shown in [Rui23].
As Example 4.5 already suggests, the notion of adjunctions, companionships and conjunctions are closely related. The following observation attests to this as well.

Proposition 4.8. Let $f: x \rightarrow y$ be a vertical arrow in a double Segal space $\mathcal{P}$ with a companion $F: x \rightarrow y$ and a conjoint $G: y \rightarrow x$. Then the pair $(F, G)$ forms an adjunction in the horizontal fragment $\operatorname{Hor}(\mathcal{P})$.

Proof. The proof is analogous to the proof of the strict case [Shu08, Proposition 5.3]. The candidate unit $\eta$ for the adjunction is defined by the pasting
![img-35.jpeg](img-35.jpeg)

of the companionship and conjunction unit. The candidate counit $\epsilon$ is given by the pasting of the companionship and conjunction counit:
![img-36.jpeg](img-36.jpeg)

It now readily follows from the triangle identities for companionships and conjunctions that $\eta$ and $\epsilon$ satisfy the triangle identities for adjunctions.
4.1. Homotopy coherence. We will now show that every companionship uniquely upgrades to a homotopy coherent one. To make this statement concrete, we will need to set up some notation.
Definition 4.9. The free-living companionship is the (discrete) double Segal space defined by

$$
\operatorname{comp}:=\operatorname{Sq}([1])
$$

The dual free-living conjunction is given by

$$
\operatorname{conj}:=\operatorname{comp}^{\text {hop }} \text {. }
$$

Definition 4.10. The free-living lower triangle is the double Segal space that can be pictured as

$$
L=\begin{aligned}
& 0=0 \\
& \| \Downarrow \\
& 0 \rightarrow 1
\end{aligned}
$$

It is defined by the pushout square
![img-37.jpeg](img-37.jpeg)
of bisimplicial spaces.
Notation 4.11. If $\mathcal{P}$ is a double Segal space, then we will write

$$
C_{\mathcal{P}} \subset \operatorname{Map}_{\mathrm{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\circ 2}\right)}(L, \mathcal{P})
$$

for the subspace spanned by the companionship units.
The remainder of this section is dedicated to proving the following two statements:
Theorem 4.12. Let $\mathcal{P}$ be a double Segal space. Then restriction along the canonical inclusion $L \rightarrow$ comp induces an equivalence

$$
\operatorname{Map}_{\mathrm{Cat}^{2}(\mathcal{S})}(\operatorname{comp}, \mathcal{P}) \xrightarrow{\simeq} C_{\mathcal{P}}
$$

Equivalently, if $\eta$ is a companionship unit in $\mathcal{P}$, then the fiber

$$
\operatorname{Map}_{\mathrm{Cat}^{2}(\mathcal{S})}(\operatorname{comp}, \mathcal{P})_{\eta}=\operatorname{Map}_{\mathrm{Cat}^{2}(\mathcal{S})}(\operatorname{comp}, \mathcal{P}) \times_{\operatorname{Map}_{\mathrm{Cat}^{2}(\mathcal{S})}(L, \mathcal{P})}\{\eta\}
$$

is contractible.
Theorem 4.13. Suppose that $\mathcal{P}$ is a double Segal space so that $\operatorname{Hor}(\mathcal{P})$ is locally complete. Then the restriction arrow

$$
\operatorname{Map}_{\mathrm{Cat}^{2}(\mathcal{S})}(\operatorname{comp}, \mathcal{P}) \rightarrow \operatorname{Map}_{\mathrm{Cat}^{2}(\mathcal{S})}([1]_{\epsilon}, \mathcal{P})
$$

is a monomorphism with image given by the subspace of vertical arrows of $\mathcal{P}$ that admit a companion.

Remark 4.14. In the context of (strict) double categories, Theorem 4.13 can be recovered as a special case of a theorem of Grandis and Paré [GP04, Theorem 1.8].

One may formally deduce the following results by applying the transpose $(-)^{t}$ and horizontal opposite $(-)^{\text {hop }}$ dualities.

Corollary 4.15. Suppose that $\mathcal{P}$ is a double Segal space so that $\operatorname{Vert}(\mathcal{P})$ is locally complete. Then the restriction arrow

$$
\operatorname{Map}_{\mathrm{Cat}^{2}(\delta)}(\operatorname{comp}, \mathcal{P}) \rightarrow \operatorname{Map}_{\mathrm{Cat}^{2}(\delta)}\left([1]_{h}, \mathcal{P}\right)
$$

is a monomorphism with image given by the subspace of horizontal arrows of $\mathcal{P}$ that are a companion.

Corollary 4.16. Suppose that $\mathcal{P}$ is a double Segal space. Then the following assertions holds:

- if $\operatorname{Hor}(\mathcal{P})$ is locally complete, then the restriction map

$$
\operatorname{Map}_{\mathrm{Cat}^{2}(\delta)}(\operatorname{conj}, \mathcal{P}) \rightarrow \operatorname{Map}_{\mathrm{Cat}^{2}(\delta)}\left([1]_{v}, \mathcal{P}\right)
$$

is a monomorphism with image given by the subspace of vertical arrows of $\mathcal{P}$ that admit a conjoint,

- if $\operatorname{Vert}(\mathcal{P})$ is locally complete, then the restriction map

$$
\operatorname{Map}_{\mathrm{Cat}^{2}(\delta)}(\operatorname{conj}, \mathcal{P}) \rightarrow \operatorname{Map}_{\mathrm{Cat}^{2}(\delta)}\left([1]_{h}, \mathcal{P}\right)
$$

is a monomorphism with image given by the subspace of horizontal arrows of $\mathcal{P}$ that are a conjoint.

Remark 4.17. In particular, note that every locally complete double Segal space $\mathcal{P}$ meets the conditions that are posed in Theorem 4.13, Corollary 4.15 and Corollary 4.16.

Corollary 4.18. The full subcategory spanned by the double Segal spaces $\mathcal{P}$ for which:

- Hor( $\mathcal{P})$ is locally complete,
- every vertical arrow of $\mathcal{P}$ admits a companion,
is a reflective subcategory of $\mathrm{Cat}^{2}(\mathcal{S})$, and particular, closed under limits.
Proof. On account of Theorem 4.13, this is precisely the full subcategory of double Segal spaces local with respect to the maps $[1 ; f]_{h} \rightarrow[1]_{h}$ and $[1]_{v} \rightarrow$ comp.

Remark 4.19. In [SS86], Schanuel and Street define the free-living adjunction (gaunt) 2category
$a b j$,
and show that every adjunction in a 2-category can be upgraded to a functor out of this 2category. This result was then upgraded by Riehl-Verity to the ( $\infty, 2$ )-categorical context [RV16], where it is shown that every left adjoint arrow in an ( $\infty, 2$ )-category uniquely (up to contractible choice) extends to a functor out of the free-living adjunction.

One may combine Example 4.5 and Corollary 4.16 to conclude that the ( $\infty, 2$ )-category obtained by applying the left adjoint $\mathrm{Gr}(-)$ of the squares functor $\mathrm{Sq}: \mathrm{Cat}_{(\infty, 2)} \rightarrow \mathrm{DblCat}_{\infty}^{\mathrm{f}}$ to the free-living conjunction, carries the same universal property of $a b j$ exhibited by Riehl-Verity. Consequently, we deduce that there is an equivalence

$$
\operatorname{Gr}(\operatorname{conj}) \simeq \mathrm{abj}
$$

In fact, one can write down an explicit functor $\operatorname{conj} \rightarrow \mathrm{Sq}(\mathrm{abj})$ using the description of the free-living adjunction of Schanuel-Street. If one succeeds to show that the adjunct map $\operatorname{Gr}(\operatorname{conj}) \rightarrow \mathrm{abj}$ is an equivalence - without reasoning with universal properties then Corollary 4.16 can be used to provide an independent proof of the main result of Riehl-Verity [RV16].

4.2. A special extension theorem. The main ingredient of the proof of Theorem 4.12 and Theorem 4.13 is a special extension result for double Segal spaces with respect to companionship units. We first set up the necessary notation.

Notation 4.20. We will consider the quotient $L[n, m]$ that is defined by the pushout square
![img-38.jpeg](img-38.jpeg)
of bisimplicial spaces, so that $L[1,1]=L$.
Notation 4.21. Let $k \geq 0$ and suppose that $S$ is a subset of $\{0, \ldots, k\}$. Then we will use the notation of [Joy08, Subsection 2.2.1] and consider the following simplicial subset

$$
\Lambda^{S}[k]:=\bigcup_{i \in\{0, \ldots, k\} \backslash S} d_{i}[k-1] \subset[k]
$$

For $n, m \geq 0$ and subsets $S$ and $T$ of $[n]$ and $[m]$ respectively, we will consider the bisimplicial subset

$$
\Lambda^{S, T}[n, m]:=\Lambda^{S}[n]_{h} \times[m]_{\nu} \cup_{\Lambda^{S}[n]_{h} \times \Lambda^{T}[m]_{\nu}}[n]_{h} \times \Lambda^{T}[m]_{\nu} \subset[n, m]
$$

Whenever $S \subset\{0, \ldots, n-1\}$ and $T \subset\{0, \ldots, m-1\}$, we will consider the quotients
![img-39.jpeg](img-39.jpeg)

For $n \geq 1$ and $m \geq 2$, we have a map

$$
L^{\cup n} \cong\{1, \ldots, n\} \times L \rightarrow \Lambda_{L}^{S, T}[n, m]
$$

where the restriction to $\{i\} \times L$ factors through the $(1,1)$-bisimplex

$$
[\{0 \leq i\},\{0 \leq 1\}):\{i\} \times[1,1] \rightarrow \Lambda^{S, T}[n, m]
$$

For brevity, we will also make use of the notation

$$
\Gamma_{L}^{T}[n, m]:=\Lambda_{L}^{\#, T}[n, m]
$$

Let $\mathcal{P}$ be a double Segal space, and suppose that we are given a map $\sigma: \Gamma_{L}^{0}[n, m] \rightarrow \mathcal{P}$ of bisimplicial spaces with $n \geq 1$ and $m \geq 2$. Moreover, we impose the condition that each restriction $\sigma\{(i\} \times L): L \rightarrow \mathcal{P}$ classifies a companionship unit for $i=1, \ldots, n$. The special extension theorem that we will prove, asserts that the dotted lift in the diagram
![img-40.jpeg](img-40.jpeg)
exists under these conditions, and that it is unique up to contractible choice. Here the left vertical arrow is the inclusion.

$k: y \rightarrow b$ and two 2-cells

# 6. Application: double $\infty$-categories of $(\infty, 2)$-Functors 

The goal of this section is to give an application of Theorem 5.4 to ( $\infty, 2$ )-category theory. Given two ( $\infty, 2$ )-categories $\mathcal{X}$ and $\mathcal{Y}$, we will first show that one can construct a double $\infty$-category

$$
\mathbb{F} \text { un }^{\operatorname{lax}}(\mathcal{X}, \mathcal{Y})
$$

with:

- the objects given by functors $\mathcal{X} \rightarrow \mathcal{Y}$,
- the vertical arrows given by natural transformations between functors $\mathcal{X} \rightarrow \mathcal{Y}$,
- the horizontal arrows given by lax natural transformations between functors $\mathcal{X} \rightarrow$ $\mathcal{Y}$,
as a particular vertical cotensor product. We will then show that one can use Theorem 5.4 to recover Haugseng's recognition theorem for adjunctions in ( $\infty, 2$ )-categories of functors and lax natural transformations [Hau21, Theorem 4.6], for a particular choice of model for the Gray tensor product (cf. Remark 6.3).
6.1. The Gray tensor product. There is a wide array of different approaches to defining the Gray tensor product for ( $\infty, 2$ )-categories. A nice summary of the different models can be found in the introduction of [CM23]. Since we have developed enough theory, we can give a brief and reasonably self-contained treatment of a model of this tensor product using double $\infty$-categorical technology that was proposed by Gaitsgory and Rozenblyum [GR17, Section 10.4.5]. The following is justified by Corollary 3.59:
Definition 6.1. The Gray tensor product of ( $\infty, 2$ )-categories $\mathcal{X}$ and $\mathcal{Y}$ is defined to be the (essentially) unique ( $\infty, 2$ )-category $\mathcal{X} \otimes \mathcal{Y}$ with the property that

$$
\operatorname{Map}_{\mathrm{Cat}_{(\infty, 2)}}(\mathcal{X} \otimes \mathcal{Y}, \mathbb{Z}) \simeq \operatorname{Map}_{\mathrm{DblCat}_{\infty}^{\prime}}\left(\mathcal{X}_{h} \times \mathcal{Y}_{v}, \mathrm{Sq}(\mathbb{Z})\right)
$$

naturally for all $\mathcal{Z} \in \mathrm{Cat}_{(\infty, 2)}$.
Note that the above definition is functorial in both variables so that we obtain a functor

$$
(-) \otimes(-): \operatorname{Cat}_{(\infty, 2)} \times \operatorname{Cat}_{(\infty, 2)} \rightarrow \operatorname{Cat}_{(\infty, 2)}
$$

Remark 6.2. It directly follows from these definitions that the Gray tensor product preserves colimits in each variable and that $[n] \otimes[m] \in \mathrm{Cat}_{(\infty, 2)}$ agrees with the strict Gray tensor product of $[n]$ and $[m]$ for all $[n],[m] \in \Delta$.

Remark 6.3. This definition of the Gray tensor product has not yet been compared to other constructions of Gray tensor products that appear in the literature.

However, we can say something about its restriction to ( $\infty, 1$ )-categories: the restricted bifunctor $(-) \otimes(-): \mathrm{Cat}_{\infty} \times \mathrm{Cat}_{\infty} \rightarrow \mathrm{Cat}_{(\infty, 2)}$ is the unique one that preserves colimits in each variable and restricts to the strict Gray tensor product on $\Delta \times \Delta$. In light of [HHLN21, Proposition 5.1.9], the Gray tensor product of Gagna, Harpaz and Lanari [GHL21] satisfies these conditions, thus it coincides with $(-) \otimes(-)$ when restricted to $(\infty, 1)$-categories.

To compare with other Gray tensor products in full generality, one can readily compute the values of $[1 ; 1] \otimes[1]$ and $[1 ; 1] \otimes[1 ; 1]$ in terms of certain pushouts by using the description $[1 ; 1]_{h}=[0,1]^{1 / 2} \cup_{[0,0]^{1 / 2}}[1,1]$. This yields fundamental formulas where the only Gray tensor products appearing are reduced to the form $([1] \times[1]) \otimes[1]$ and $([1] \times[1]) \otimes([1] \times[1])$. If these formulas are true for other Gray tensor products, this allows you to reduce to the above case since every $(\infty, 2)$-category can be written as a canonical colimit of the free cells $[0],[1]$ and $[1 ; 1]$.

(2) $u$ is strict and admits a conjoint in $\mathbb{F} \operatorname{un}^{\operatorname{lax}}(\mathcal{X}, \mathcal{Y})$,
(3) $u$ is strict and each component $u_{x}: h(x) \rightarrow k(x)$ is a left adjoint in $\mathcal{Y}$.

If these equivalent conditions are met, then for any arrow $x \rightarrow y$ in $\mathcal{X}$, the horizontal morphisms in the lax naturality square of the right adjoint $v$
![img-74.jpeg](img-74.jpeg)
are given by left adjoints to $v_{x}$ and $v_{y}$, and the filling 2-cell is given by the mate of the corresponding naturality square of $u$.

Remark 6.10. A first complete proof of Theorem 6.7, albeit using a different definition of the Gray tensor product, was recently given by Abellán, Gagna and Haugseng [AGH24].
Remark 6.11. One readily verifies that Theorem 6.7 and Corollary 6.9 also go through whenever $\mathcal{X} \in \operatorname{PSh}\left(\Delta^{\times 2}\right)_{\text {deg }}$, and $\mathcal{Y}$ is a locally complete 2 -fold Segal space. In this case, one can still define $\mathbb{F} \operatorname{un}^{\operatorname{lax}}(\mathcal{X}, \mathcal{Y}):=[\mathcal{X}, \operatorname{Sq}(\mathcal{Y})]$, which will now be a locally complete double Segal space.

abstract:
We demonstrate that companionships and conjunctions in double
$\infty$-categories -- and more generally, in double Segal spaces -- extend to
functors out of the free-living companionship and conjunction respectively.
Specifically, we prove that these extensions are (homotopically) unique: the
corresponding spaces of extensions are contractible under suitable completeness
assumptions. The developed theory is then put to use to give a characterization
of companions and conjoints in functor double Segal spaces in terms of
so-called companionable and conjointable 2-cells. We end with an application of
our results to $(\infty,2)$-category theory.
